After his death and especially after the death oi Terence in 159, when no new plays were being written, the theatre managers began to produce for a second time the plays ot Plautus which they had in their possession. For such second presentations the plays were cut down in some scenes and expanded in others, and the prologues were in some cases (as the Casina) entirely rewritten. Further, as Plautus had been the most popular of the Roman writers of comedy‚ plays not written by him were probably brought out under his name. When, therefore, in the second halt ot the ¹ second century nc, the early Roman literature became the subject ot study and of learned commentary, many interpo lations and revisions had already found a place in the text, and the number ot plays actually written by Plautus was in doubt. One tradition set the number as high as 130, other traditions fixed it at 100 or at 40. The names of 55 plays attributed to Plautus by grammarians have come down to us. By a comparison of different lists, Varro, the greatest ot the earlier Roman grammarians, selected 21 plays as undoubtedly genuine, and his authority was strong enough to fix the tradition that these plays constituted the works ot Plautus Whether they were gathered into a single volume in his time is not certain, but they were certainly so eol· lected by the end ot the first century after Christ, while other plays existed only singly in scattered copies, and have not come down to us.
